{"title_page": "David Eckstein", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name        = David Eckstein\n| image       = David Eckstein 02.JPG\n| width       = 250\n| alt         =\n| caption     = Eckstein with the San Diego Padres\n| position    = [[Shortstop]] \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1975|1|20|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Sanford, Florida]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| bats        = Right\n| throws      = Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate   = April 3\n| debutyear   = 2001\n| debutteam   = Anaheim Angels\n|finalleague = MLB\n| finaldate   = October 3\n| finalyear   = 2010\n| finalteam   = San Diego Padres\n|statleague = MLB\n| stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value  = .280\n| stat2label  = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value  = 35\n| stat3label  = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value  = 392\n| teams       = \n* [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim|Anaheim Angels]] ({{mlby|2001}}\u2013{{mlby|2004}})\n* [[St. Louis Cardinals]] ({{mlby|2005}}\u2013{{mlby|2007}})\n* [[Toronto Blue Jays]] ({{mlby|2008}})\n* [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] ({{mlby|2008}})\n* [[San Diego Padres]] ({{mlby|2009}}\u2013{{mlby|2010}})\n| awards      = \n* 2\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2005 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2005]], [[2006 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2006]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|2002}}, {{wsy|2006}})\n* [[World Series MVP]] (2006)\n}}\n\n'''David Mark Eckstein''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u025b|k|\u0283|t|a\u026a|n}}; born January 20, 1975) is a retired American professional [[baseball]] player who was an [[infielder]] in [[Major League Baseball]] for ten seasons. He played [[college baseball]] for the [[University of Florida]] and played professionally for the [[Anaheim Angels]], [[St. Louis Cardinals]], [[Toronto Blue Jays]], [[Arizona Diamondbacks]], and [[San Diego Padres]]. Eckstein won the [[2006 World Series|2006]] [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award]]. He is currently serving as a special assistant in the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] operations department.\n\n== Amateur career ==\n\n=== High school ===\nEckstein played baseball all four years at [[Seminole High School (Seminole County, Florida)|Seminole High School]] in [[Sanford, Florida]]. He was a two-time all-state selection, and a prominent member of a state championship team. He was also a member of the [[National Honor Society]] and the [[Fellowship of Christian Athletes]]. Eckstein was voted \"Most Helpful\" in the Class of 1993.\n\nIn addition, Eckstein played [[American Legion Baseball]] for Post 53.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.legion.org/baseball/alumni/david-eckstein |title=David Eckstein |website=The American Legion |access-date=2016-03-16}}</ref>\n\n=== College ===\nAt the [[University of Florida]] in Gainesville, Florida, Eckstein was a [[walk-on (sports)|walk-on]] player for coach [[Joe Arnold]]'s [[Florida Gators baseball]] team in the fall of 1994; he later earned an [[athletic scholarship]]. A standout in the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC), he was a first-team All-SEC selection in 1995 and 1996, a first-team [[All-American]] in 1996, a three-time SEC Academic Honor Roll selection (1995\u20131997), and the first two-time Academic All-American in Gators baseball history. Eckstein was a member of the 1996 Gators squad that finished third in the [[1996 College World Series|College World Series]]. He was inducted into the University of Florida Athletic Hall of Fame as a \"Gator Great\" in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gatorfclub.org/hall-of-fame/greats |title=Gator Greats |website=F Club |access-date=December 13, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gatorzone.com/story.php?id=12022 |title=Nine Members Inducted Into University of Florida Athletics Hall of Fame |date=April 13, 2007 |website=GatorZone.com |access-date=July 21, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924044847/http://www.gatorzone.com/story.php?id=12022 |archive-date=2015-09-24}}</ref>\n\nEckstein also played for the [[Harrisonburg Turks]] of the Valley Baseball League in Harrisonburg, Virginia.\n\n== Professional career ==\n\n=== Anaheim Angels ===\nEckstein was drafted by the [[Boston Red Sox]] in the 19th round of the [[1997 Major League Baseball Draft|1997 amateur draft]], and selected off waivers by the [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim|Anaheim Angels]] on August 16, 2000. During the {{mlby|2002}} championship year, he led the major leagues with three [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slams]], including grand slams in back-to-back games against the [[Toronto Blue Jays]], one of which was a [[Walk-off home run|walk-off]] grand slam leading the Angels to complete the sweep over Toronto, at a time when the Angels were 7\u201314. After the sweep of the Jays, the Angels went on to win 20 of their next 23 games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/ANA/2002_sched.shtml |title=2002 Anaheim Angels Schedule, Box Scores and Splits |work=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\n=== St. Louis Cardinals ===\nAt the end of the [[2004 St. Louis Cardinals season|2004 season]], Eckstein was part of a \"shortstop [[merry-go-round]],\" in which three [[free agent]] shortstops swapped teams: [[\u00c9dgar Renter\u00eda]] went from the Cardinals to the [[Boston Red Sox]], [[Orlando Cabrera]] went from the Red Sox to the Angels, and Eckstein went from the Angels to the Cardinals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=schwarz_alan&id=2014780 |title=Changing places, not positions |accessdate=2009-01-24 |last=Schwarz |first=Alan |date=2005-03-23 |work=[[ESPN.com]]}}</ref>\n \nIn his first seven seasons, he amassed 1,079 hits while batting .286. He was voted to the [[National League]] [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] team in [[2005 St. Louis Cardinals season|2005]], along with teammates [[Chris Carpenter]], [[Albert Pujols]], [[Jason Isringhausen]] and [[Jim Edmonds]]. He was a late addition to the [[2006 St. Louis Cardinals season|2006]] All-Star team. In 3,772 regular season [[at-bat]]s, Eckstein [[Strikeout|struck out]] only 305 times, with a total of 22 in [[2007 St. Louis Cardinals season|2007]].\n\n[[Image:David Eckstein.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Eckstein signing autographs before a May 30th game against the [[Houston Astros]] in [[2006 St. Louis Cardinals season|2006]] as a member of the Cardinals.]]\n\nEckstein was a fan favorite in St. Louis, who considered him to be a \"pesky\" hitter<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/10/sports/baseball-spotlight-national-league-scouting-report.html |title=Baseball: Spotlight; National League Scouting Report |first=Ben |last=Shpigel |date=10 October 2006 |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> (he chokes up on the bat about 2&nbsp;inches<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/27/sports/27iht-base.3306948.html |title=Baseball: Dynamo powers Cardinals' victory |first=Tyler |last=Kepner |date=27 October 2006 |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>). On [[Mother's Day (United States)|Mother's Day]], May 14, 2006, Eckstein was one of more than 50 hitters who brandished a [[pink bat]] to benefit the [http://www.komen.org Breast Cancer Foundation].\n\nAs a member of the [[2006 World Series]] Champion St. Louis Cardinals, Eckstein was named the [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award|World Series MVP]]. Following a 1\u201311 start in the first 2 games of the World Series, Eckstein went 8 for 22 with 4 [[Run batted in|RBI]] and scored 3 [[Run (baseball)|runs]] in the series, including going 4-for-5 with three [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] in game 4. The World Series victory with the Cardinals made Eckstein one of few{{how many|date=October 2013}} starting shortstops who have won a World Series in both the American and National Leagues.\n\nEckstein was brought back in front of over 47,000 fans to throw out the first pitch of Game 6 of the World Series in St. Louis on October 27, 2011.\n\n=== Toronto Blue Jays ===\nOn November 5, 2007, Eckstein became a [[free agent]] along with [[Kip Wells]], [[Troy Percival]], and [[Miguel Cairo]]. On December 13, 2007, he signed a one-year, $4.5 million contract with the [[Toronto Blue Jays]].\n\n=== Arizona Diamondbacks ===\nOn August 31, [[2008 Arizona Diamondbacks season|2008]], Eckstein was traded to the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] for minor league [[pitcher]] [[Chad Beck]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://arizona.diamondbacks.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20080831&content_id=3397844&vkey=pr_ari&fext=.jsp&c_id=ari |title=D-backs acquire David Eckstein from Blue Jays |date=2008-08-31 |work=Arizona Diamondbacks |access-date=2008-08-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610133235/http://arizona.diamondbacks.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20080831&content_id=3397844&vkey=pr_ari&fext=.jsp&c_id=ari |archive-date=2011-06-10 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== San Diego Padres ===\nOn January 15, 2009, he signed a discounted one-year contract with the [[San Diego Padres]] on the condition that he would play primarily [[second base]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090115&content_id=3745472&vkey=news_sd&fext=.jsp&c_id=sd |title=Padres bolster infield with Eckstein, Veteran shortstop eager to move back to second base |accessdate=2009-01-24 |last=Brock |first=Corey |date=2009-01-15 |website=[[MLB.com]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306064818/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090115&content_id=3745472&vkey=news_sd&fext=.jsp&c_id=sd |archive-date=2009-03-06}}</ref> On August 22, 2009, the [[San Diego Padres]] extended Eckstein's contract through [[2010 San Diego Padres season|2010]].\n\nEckstein did not join a team for the {{Baseball year|2011}} season. In June, it was reported that he received offers from the Padres and other teams, but opted to not play baseball. He is working for his wife, actress [[Ashley Eckstein]].<ref name=latJune292011>{{cite news |last=DiGiovanna |first=Mike |title=David Eckstein says he is not officially retired from baseball |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jun/29/sports/la-sp-0630-angels-fyi-20110630 |accessdate=6 July 2011 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=29 June 2011}}</ref> He officially retired on January 22, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2012-01-22/david-eckstein-retires |title=Former World Series MVP David Eckstein retires |date=2012-01-22 |website=Sporting News |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120123115928/http://aol.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2012-01-22/david-eckstein-retires |archive-date=2012-01-23}}</ref>\n \n\n===Career Statistics===\nIn 1,311 games over 10 seasons, Eckstein posted a .280 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] (1,414-for-5,041) with 701 [[run (baseball)|runs]], 232 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], 20 [[triple (baseball)|triples]], 35 [[home runs]], 392 [[RBI]], 123 [[stolen bases]], 376 [[bases on balls]], .345 [[on-base percentage]] and .355 [[slugging percentage]]. He finished his career with a .982 [[fielding percentage]] playing at shortstop and second base. In 44 postseason games, he hit .278 (49-for-176) with 26 runs, 4 doubles, 2 home runs, 18 RBI, 7 stolen bases and 12 walks.\n\n== Post-playing career ==\nEckstein became a candidate for induction into the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum]] for the first time on November 9, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bloom |first=Barry M. |url=http://m.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article/156820432/griffey-hoffman-highlight-hall-of-fame-ballot |title=Junior, Hoffman highlight HOF ballot newcomers |website=MLB.com |date=November 9, 2015 |accessdate=November 10, 2015}}</ref> He earned two votes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2605588-2016-bbwaa-hall-of-fame-election-results-announced |title=2016 BBWAA Hall of Fame Election Results Announced |first=Joseph |last=Zucker |website=Bleacher Report}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nEckstein was born in [[Sanford, Florida]]. He married actress [[Ashley Eckstein|Ashley Drane]] on November 26, 2005, at his family church in Sanford, Florida, followed by a reception at [[Walt Disney World]].<ref name=phil2006>{{cite news |title=Little David Becomes A Goliath |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=06VjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=biUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2739,12080044&dq=david+eckstein+ashley+drane&hl=en |accessdate=21 May 2011 |newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |date=29 October 2006}}</ref> He is a fan of [[professional wrestling]], having made public appearances with [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] during the 2006 World Series and on February 11, 2007, he [[Manager (professional wrestling)|co-managed]] (along with [[Tampa Bay Rays]] outfielder [[Johnny Damon]]) TNA wrestler Lance Hoyt for his match with current [[White Sox]] conditioning coach [[Dale Torborg]], managed by Sox catcher [[A. J. Pierzynski]] at TNA's [[Against All Odds (2007)|Against All Odds]] pay-per-view.\n\nAfter his older brother, [[Rick Eckstein|Rick]], was hired after the 2018 season as the hitting coach for the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]],<ref name=latJune292011 /> David was hired in February as a special assistant in their baseball operations department.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wruf.com/headlines/2019/02/05/former-gator-david-eckstein-gets-a-new-job-with-his-brother/ |title=Former Gator David Eckstein Gets a New Job With His Brother |first=Sophia |last=LaFrance |date=February 5, 2019 |work=[[WRUF-FM]]}}</ref>\n\n== Career highlights ==\n* Holiday Inn Look Again Player of the Year (2006)\n* 2-time World Series Champion (2002 Anaheim Angels, 2006 St. Louis Cardinals)\n* [[World Series MVP]] (2006)\n* 2-time All-Star (2005, 2006)\n* [[Babe Ruth Award]] winner (2006)\n* Inaugural winner of the Major League Baseball Players Alumni Association's [[Heart & Hustle Award]] (2005)\n* Number retired by the [[Trenton Thunder]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Eckstein's #2 to be Retired Wednesday, May 8 |url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130506&content_id=46777150&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_t567&sid=t567 |website=Trenton Thunder |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511005144/http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130506&content_id=46777150&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_t567&sid=t567 |archive-date=2013-05-11}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Baseball|Biography}}\n* [[Florida Gators]]\n* [[List of Florida Gators baseball players]]\n* [[List of University of Florida Athletic Hall of Fame members]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Eckstein, David, with Greg Brown, ''Have Heart'', Builder's Stone Publishing, Lake Mary, Florida (2006). {{ISBN|0-9791504-0-X}}.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat|David Eckstein}}\n{{Baseballstats|mlb=275930|espn=4625|br=e/eckstda01|fangraphs=10|brm=eckste001dav}}\n\n{{2002 Anaheim Angels}}\n{{2006 St. Louis Cardinals}}\n{{World Series MVPs}}\n{{Babe Ruth Award}}\n{{Heart & Hustle Award}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eckstein, David}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All-American college baseball players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:American Christians]]\n[[Category:Anaheim Angels players]]\n[[Category:Arizona Diamondbacks players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Florida]]\n[[Category:Dunedin Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:Edmonton Trappers players]]\n[[Category:Florida Gators baseball players]]\n[[Category:Lowell Spinners players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball shortstops]]\n[[Category:National League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Pawtucket Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sanford, Florida]]\n[[Category:San Diego Padres players]]\n[[Category:Sarasota Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:Seminole High School (Seminole County, Florida) alumni]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:Trenton Thunder players]]\n[[Category:University of Florida alumni]]\n[[Category:World Series Most Valuable Player Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name        = David Eckstein\n| image       = David Eckstein 02.JPG\n| width       = 250\n| alt         =\n| caption     = Eckstein with the San Diego Padres\n| position    = [[Shortstop]] \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1975|1|20|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Sanford, Florida]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| bats        = Right\n| throws      = Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate   = April 3\n| debutyear   = 2001\n| debutteam   = Anaheim Angels\n|finalleague = MLB\n| finaldate   = October 3\n| finalyear   = 2010\n| finalteam   = San Diego Padres\n|statleague = MLB\n| stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value  = .280\n| stat2label  = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value  = 35\n| stat3label  = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value  = 392\n| teams       = \n* [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim|Anaheim Angels]] ({{mlby|2001}}\u2013{{mlby|2004}})\n* [[St. Louis Cardinals]] ({{mlby|2005}}\u2013{{mlby|2007}})\n* [[Toronto Blue Jays]] ({{mlby|2008}})\n* [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] ({{mlby|2008}})\n* [[San Diego Padres]] ({{mlby|2009}}\u2013{{mlby|2010}})\n| awards      = \n* 2\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2005 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2005]], [[2006 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2006]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|2002}}, {{wsy|2006}})\n* [[World Series MVP]] (2006)\n}}\n\n'''David Mark Eckstein''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u025b|k|\u0283|t|a\u026a|n}}; born January 20, 1975) is a retired American professional [[baseball]] player who was an [[infielder]] in [[Major League Baseball]] for ten seasons.  He played [[college baseball]] for the [[University of Florida]] and played professionally for the [[Anaheim Angels]], [[St. Louis Cardinals]], [[Toronto Blue Jays]], [[Arizona Diamondbacks]], and [[San Diego Padres]]. Eckstein won the [[2006 World Series|2006]] [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award]].  He is currently serving as a special assistant in the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] operations department.\n\n== Amateur career ==\n\n=== High school ===\nEckstein played baseball all four years at [[Seminole High School (Seminole County, Florida)|Seminole High School]] in [[Sanford, Florida]].  He was a two-time all-state selection, and a prominent member of a state championship team. He was also a member of the [[National Honor Society]] and the [[Fellowship of Christian Athletes]].  Eckstein was voted \"Most Helpful\" in the Class of 1993.\n\nIn addition, Eckstein played [[American Legion Baseball]] for Post 53.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legion.org/baseball/alumni/david-eckstein|title=David Eckstein {{!}} The American Legion|website=www.legion.org|access-date=2016-03-16}}</ref>\n\n=== College ===\nAt the [[University of Florida]] in Gainesville, Florida, Eckstein was a [[walk-on (sports)|walk-on]] player for coach [[Joe Arnold]]'s [[Florida Gators baseball]] team in the fall of 1994; he later earned an [[athletic scholarship]].  A standout in the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC), he was a first-team All-SEC selection in 1995 and 1996, a first-team [[All-American]] in 1996, a three-time SEC Academic Honor Roll selection (1995\u20131997), and the first two-time Academic All-American in Gators baseball history.  Eckstein was a member of the 1996 Gators squad that finished third in the [[1996 College World Series|College World Series]].  He was inducted into the University of Florida Athletic Hall of Fame as a \"Gator Great\" in 2007.<ref>F Club, Hall of Fame, [http://www.gatorfclub.org/hall-of-fame/greats  Gator Greats].  Retrieved December 13, 2014.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.gatorzone.com/story.php?id=12022  Nine Members Inducted Into University of Florida Athletics Hall of Fame] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924044847/http://www.gatorzone.com/story.php?id=12022 |date=2015-09-24 }},\" GatorZone.com (April 13, 2007).  Retrieved July 21, 2011.</ref>\n\nEckstein also played for the Harrisonburg Turks of the Valley Baseball League in Harrisonburg, Virginia.\n\n== Professional career ==\n\n=== Anaheim Angels ===\nEckstein was drafted by the [[Boston Red Sox]] in the 19th round of the [[1997 Major League Baseball Draft|1997 amateur draft]], and selected off waivers by the [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim|Anaheim Angels]] on August 16, 2000.  During the {{mlby|2002}} championship year, he led the major leagues with three [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slams]], including grand slams in back-to-back games against the [[Toronto Blue Jays]], one of which was a [[Walk-off home run|walk-off]] grand slam leading the Angels to complete the sweep over Toronto, at a time when the Angels were 7\u201314. After the sweep of the Jays, the Angels went on to win 20 of their next 23 games.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/ANA/2002_sched.shtml 2002 Anaheim Angels Schedule, Box Scores and Splits \u2013 Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n=== St. Louis Cardinals ===\nAt the end of the [[2004 St. Louis Cardinals season|2004 season]], Eckstein was part of a \"shortstop [[merry-go-round]],\" in which three [[free agent]] shortstops swapped teams: [[\u00c9dgar Renter\u00eda]] went from the Cardinals to the [[Boston Red Sox]], [[Orlando Cabrera]] went from the Red Sox to the Angels, and Eckstein went from the Angels to the Cardinals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=schwarz_alan&id=2014780 |title=Changing places, not positions |accessdate=2009-01-24|last=Schwarz |first=Alan |date=2005-03-23|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]}}</ref>\n \nIn his first seven seasons, he amassed 1,079 hits while batting .286.  He was voted to the [[National League]] [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] team in [[2005 St. Louis Cardinals season|2005]], along with teammates [[Chris Carpenter]], [[Albert Pujols]], [[Jason Isringhausen]] and [[Jim Edmonds]].  He was a late addition to the [[2006 St. Louis Cardinals season|2006]] All-Star team. In 3,772 regular season [[at-bat]]s, Eckstein [[Strikeout|struck out]] only 305 times, with a total of 22 in [[2007 St. Louis Cardinals season|2007]].\n\n[[Image:David Eckstein.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Eckstein signing autographs before a May 30th game against the [[Houston Astros]] in [[2006 St. Louis Cardinals season|2006]] as a member of the Cardinals.]]\n\nEckstein was a fan favorite in St. Louis, who considered him to be a \"pesky\" hitter<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/10/sports/baseball-spotlight-national-league-scouting-report.html Baseball: Spotlight; National League Scouting Report, ''The New York Times''], 10 October 2006</ref> (he chokes up on the bat about 2&nbsp;inches<ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/10/27/sports/base.php \"Baseball: Dynamo powers Cardinals' victory\", ''International Herald Tribune''], 27 October 2006</ref>).  On [[Mother's Day (United States)|Mother's Day]], May 14, 2006, Eckstein was one of more than 50 hitters who brandished a [[pink bat]] to benefit the [http://www.komen.org Breast Cancer Foundation].\n\nAs a member of the [[2006 World Series]] Champion St. Louis Cardinals, Eckstein was named the [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award|World Series MVP]].  Following a 1\u201311 start in the first 2 games of the World Series, Eckstein went 8 for 22 with 4 [[Run batted in|RBI]] and scored 3 [[Run (baseball)|runs]] in the series, including going 4-for-5 with three [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] in game 4.  The World Series victory with the Cardinals made Eckstein one of few{{how many|date=October 2013}} starting shortstops who have won a World Series in both the American and National Leagues.\n\nEckstein was brought back in front of over 47,000 fans to throw out the first pitch of Game 6 of the World Series in St. Louis on October 27, 2011.\n\n=== Toronto Blue Jays ===\nOn November 5, 2007, Eckstein became a [[free agent]] along with [[Kip Wells]], [[Troy Percival]], and [[Miguel Cairo]]. On December 13, 2007, he signed a one-year, $4.5 million contract with the [[Toronto Blue Jays]].\n\n=== Arizona Diamondbacks ===\nOn August 31, [[2008 Arizona Diamondbacks season|2008]], Eckstein was traded to the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] for minor league [[pitcher]] [[Chad Beck]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://arizona.diamondbacks.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20080831&content_id=3397844&vkey=pr_ari&fext=.jsp&c_id=ari |title=D-backs acquire David Eckstein from Blue Jays |access-date=2008-08-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610133235/http://arizona.diamondbacks.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20080831&content_id=3397844&vkey=pr_ari&fext=.jsp&c_id=ari |archive-date=2011-06-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== San Diego Padres ===\nOn January 15, 2009, he signed a discounted one-year contract with the [[San Diego Padres]] on the condition that he would play primarily [[second base]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090115&content_id=3745472&vkey=news_sd&fext=.jsp&c_id=sd |title=Padres bolster infield with Eckstein Veteran shortstop eager to move back to second base |accessdate=2009-01-24|last=Brock |first=Corey |date=2009-01-15 |publisher=[[MLB.com]]}}</ref>  On August 22, 2009, the [[San Diego Padres]] extended Eckstein's contract through [[2010 San Diego Padres season|2010]].\n\nEckstein did not join a team for the {{Baseball year|2011}} season.  In June, it was reported that he received offers from the Padres and other teams, but opted to not play baseball. He is working for his wife, actress [[Ashley Eckstein]].<ref name=latJune292011>{{cite news|last=DiGiovanna|first=Mike|title=David Eckstein says he is not officially retired from baseball|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jun/29/sports/la-sp-0630-angels-fyi-20110630|accessdate=6 July 2011|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=29 June 2011}}</ref> He officially retired on January 22, 2012.<ref>[http://aol.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2012-01-22/david-eckstein-retires Former World Series MVP David Eckstein retires]</ref>\n\n===Career Statistics===\nIn 1,311 games over 10 seasons, Eckstein posted a .280 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] (1,414-for-5,041) with 701 [[run (baseball)|runs]], 232 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], 20 [[triple (baseball)|triples]], 35 [[home runs]], 392 [[RBI]], 123 [[stolen bases]], 376 [[bases on balls]], .345 [[on-base percentage]] and .355 [[slugging percentage]]. He finished his career with a .982 [[fielding percentage]] playing at shortstop and second base. In 44 postseason games, he hit .278 (49-for-176) with 26 runs, 4 doubles, 2 home runs, 18 RBI, 7 stolen bases and 12 walks.\n\n== Post-playing career ==\nEckstein became a candidate for induction into the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum]] for the first time on November 9, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bloom |first=Barry M. |url=http://m.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article/156820432/griffey-hoffman-highlight-hall-of-fame-ballot |title=Junior, Hoffman highlight HOF ballot newcomers |publisher=MLB.com |date=November 9, 2015 |accessdate=November 10, 2015}}</ref> He earned two votes.<ref>[http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2605588-2016-bbwaa-hall-of-fame-election-results-announced http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2605588-2016-bbwaa-hall-of-fame-election-results-announced]</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nEckstein was born in [[Sanford, Florida]]. He married actress [[Ashley Eckstein|Ashley Drane]] on November 26, 2005, at his family church in Sanford, Florida, followed by a reception at [[Walt Disney World]].<ref name=phil2006>{{cite news|title=Little David Becomes A Goliath|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=06VjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=biUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2739,12080044&dq=david+eckstein+ashley+drane&hl=en|accessdate=21 May 2011|newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=29 October 2006}}</ref>   He is a fan of [[professional wrestling]], having made public appearances with [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] during the 2006 World Series and on February 11, 2007, he [[Manager (professional wrestling)|co-managed]] (along with [[Tampa Bay Rays]] outfielder [[Johnny Damon]]) TNA wrestler Lance Hoyt for his match with current [[White Sox]] conditioning coach [[Dale Torborg]], managed by Sox catcher [[A. J. Pierzynski]] at TNA's [[Against All Odds (2007)|Against All Odds]] pay-per-view.\n\nAfter his older brother, [[Rick Eckstein|Rick]], was hired after the 2018 season as the hitting coach for the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]],<ref name=latJune292011 /> David was hired in February as a special assistant in their baseball operations department.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Gator David Eckstein Gets a New Job With His Brother|url=http://www.wruf.com/headlines/2019/02/05/former-gator-david-eckstein-gets-a-new-job-with-his-brother/]}}</ref>\n\n== Career highlights ==\n* Holiday Inn Look Again Player of the Year (2006)\n* 2-time World Series Champion (2002 Anaheim Angels, 2006 St. Louis Cardinals)\n* [[World Series MVP]] (2006)\n* 2-time All-Star (2005, 2006)\n* [[Babe Ruth Award]] winner (2006)\n* Inaugural winner of the Major League Baseball Players Alumni Association's [[Heart & Hustle Award]] (2005)\n* Number retired by the [[Trenton Thunder]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Eckstein's #2 to be Retired Wednesday, May 8|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130506&content_id=46777150&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_t567&sid=t567|publisher=Trenton Thunder}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Baseball|Biography}}\n* [[Florida Gators]]\n* [[List of Florida Gators baseball players]]\n* [[List of University of Florida Athletic Hall of Fame members]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Eckstein, David, with Greg Brown, ''Have Heart'', Builder's Stone Publishing, Lake Mary, Florida (2006).  {{ISBN|0-9791504-0-X}}.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat|David Eckstein}}\n{{Baseballstats|mlb=275930|espn=4625|br=e/eckstda01|fangraphs=10|brm=eckste001dav}}\n\n{{2002 Anaheim Angels}}\n{{2006 St. Louis Cardinals}}\n{{World Series MVPs}}\n{{Babe Ruth Award}}\n{{Heart & Hustle Award}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eckstein, David}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All-American college baseball players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:American Christians]]\n[[Category:Anaheim Angels players]]\n[[Category:Arizona Diamondbacks players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Florida]]\n[[Category:Dunedin Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:Edmonton Trappers players]]\n[[Category:Florida Gators baseball players]]\n[[Category:Lowell Spinners players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball shortstops]]\n[[Category:National League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Pawtucket Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sanford, Florida]]\n[[Category:San Diego Padres players]]\n[[Category:Sarasota Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:Seminole High School (Seminole County, Florida) alumni]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:Trenton Thunder players]]\n[[Category:University of Florida alumni]]\n[[Category:World Series Most Valuable Player Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "Dawkeye", "label": "safe", "comment": "fmt/update references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Eckstein"}
{"title_page": "Payal Fort", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2018}}\n'''Payal Fort''' is a Historic Monument of Punjab, built by Maharaja Amar Singh of [[Patiala]] Ryasat in [[Payal, India|Payal]] with the co-operation of the\n[[Mughal Empire|Mughals]] in 1771.<ref>http://www.mykhanna.com/payal.html</ref>\n\nNow a days Fort is undertaken by [[Archaeological Survey of India]] <ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20100310/ldh1.htm#10 | title=Payal Fort: Admin gets 16 properties vacated | newspaper=Ludhiana Tribune | date=10 March 2010 | accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref> Most of the part of The Fort has been renovated by [[Archaeological Survey of India]] but some of the interior renovation work is in under process.  \n\nIn early centuries PAYAL was known as SAHIBGARH, after that Maharaja Amar Singh changed its name. The exact reason behind this does not know by anyone.\n\nThe interior  of the fort is deteriorating.<ref>http://punjabrevenue.nic.in/gaz_ldh39.htm</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Tourism in Punjab, India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Forts_in_India}}\n\n{{coord|30|43|24|N|76|3|28|E|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Ludhiana]]\n[[Category:Forts in Punjab, India]]\n\n\n{{India-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2018}}\n'''Payal Fort''' is a fort built by Maharaja Amar Singh of [[Patiala]] in [[Payal, India|Payal]] with the co-operation of the\n[[Mughal Empire|Mughals]] in 1771.<ref>http://www.mykhanna.com/payal.html</ref>At present, a public girls high school is being run from the fort.<ref>http://ludhiana.nic.in/admin/admin_mc_payal.html</ref>\n\nThis historical fort has been handed over to the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] after removing illegal encroachments.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20100310/ldh1.htm#10 | title=Payal Fort: Admin gets 16 properties vacated | newspaper=Ludhiana Tribune | date=10 March 2010 | accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe interior  of the fort is deteriorating.<ref>http://punjabrevenue.nic.in/gaz_ldh39.htm</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Tourism in Punjab, India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Forts_in_India}}\n\n{{coord|30|43|24|N|76|3|28|E|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Ludhiana]]\n[[Category:Forts in Punjab, India]]\n\n\n{{India-struct-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sukha aujla", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Payal_Fort"}
